We want to find a solution to

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}f(x)=x\end{align*}

and so we begin by defining a function

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}g(x)=f(x)-x\end{align*}

so that we can think instead of finding roots to g(x). Recall that the
Newton-Raphson Method for finding roots to a function g(x) gives a
future approximation ($x_{n+1}$) based on a current approximation
($x_n$) as

\begin{align*}x_{n+1}=x_n-\frac{g(x_n)}{g'(x_n)}.\end{align*}

Therefore, in our case

\begin{align*}x_1=x_0-\frac{g(x_0)}{g'(x_0)}=3-\frac{g(3)}{g'(3)}\end{align*}

since $x_0=3$. The task now is to find what g(3) and g'(3) are. Since
g(x)=f(x)-x then

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}g'(x)=f'(x)-1\end{align*}

so we really only need to determine f(3) and f'(3). To do this we can
use the tangent line which is also the linear approximation to f(x).
Therefore we have that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}f(x)\approx{}5x-7=5x-15+8=8+5(x-3)=f(3)+f'(3)(x-3).\end{align*}

Therefore, we have that f(3)=8 and f'(3)=5. Similarly, we then have
that,

\begin{align*}
g(3)=f(3)-3=8-3&=5\\
g'(3)=f'(3)-1=5-1&=4\end{align*}

and so we get that,

\begin{align*}x_1=3-\frac{g(3)}{g'(3)}=3-\frac{5}{4}=\frac{7}{4}.\end{align*}

Therefore the next approximation to the solution is $x_1=7/4$.
